2. Let $M(x_1,y_1)$, $N(x_2,y_2)$. From Vieta's formulas, we get $x_1+x_2= rac{8k^2}{1+2k^2}$, $x_1x_2= rac{8k^2-2}{1+2k^2}$, $y_1+y_2=k(x_1+x_2-4)=- rac{4k}{1+2k^2}$, then the midpoint G of MN is $G( rac{4k^2}{1+2k^2},- rac{2k}{1+2k^2})$;
3. The equation of the line FM is $y= rac{y_1}{x_1+1}(x+1)$. Let $x=1$, we get $P(1, rac{2y_1}{x_1+1})$. Similarly, $Q(1, rac{2y_2}{x_2+1})$. Calculate the ordinate of the midpoint H of PQ: $ rac{2y_1}{x_1+1}+ rac{2y_2}{x_2+1}= rac{2k[(x_1-2)(x_2+1)+(x_2-2)(x_1+1)]}{(x_1+1)(x_2+1)}= rac{-16k}{18k^2-1}$, that is $H(1, rac{-8k}{18k^2-1})$;
4. Calculate the slope of the line AG: $k_{AG}= rac{- rac{2k}{1+2k^2}-0}{ rac{4k^2}{1+2k^2}- rac{1}{5}}= rac{-10k}{18k^2-1}$, and the slope of the line AH: $k_{AH}= rac{ rac{-8k}{18k^2-1}-0}{1- rac{1}{5}}= rac{-10k}{18k^2-1}$;
5. Since $k_{AG}=k_{AH}$ and A is the common point, points A, G and H are collinear.

1. From $a_1a_N<0$, we know that $a_1$ and $a_N$ have opposite signs, let us assume $a_1<0$, $a_N>0$ without loss of generality;
2. Define the set $T=\{i | a_i<0, i \in \{1,2,...,N\}\}$, $T$ is a finite non-empty set. Let the maximum number in $T$ be $m$ ($1≤m≤N-1$), then $a_m<0$, $a_{m+1}≥0$;
3. From $|a_{m+1}-a_m|≤1$, we get $a_{m+1}≤a_m + 1$, and since $a_m<0$, we have $a_{m+1}<1$;
4. Combining $a_{m+1}≥0$ and all terms of the sequence are integers, we get $a_{m+1}=0$. Take $k=m+1$, then $a_k=0$;
5. If $a_1>0$, $a_N<0$, let $b_i=-a_i$, then the sequence $\{b_i\}$ satisfies $b_1<0$, $b_N>0$, and $|b_i - b_{i-1}|=|a_i - a_{i-1}|≤1$. Similarly, we can prove that there exists $b_k=0$, that is $a_k=0$;
6. In summary, there must exist $a_k=0$ in the sequence $A_N$.

1. Let $t= rac{S(A_N)}{N}$. Since $S(A_N)$ is an integer multiple of N, we get $t \in Z$;
2. Let the maximum value of the sequence $A_N$ be $M$ and the minimum value be $m$, then $Nm < S(A_N) < NM$. Divide both sides by N to get $m < t < M$;
3. Let $a_i=m$, $a_j=M$, assume $i<j$ without loss of generality. From $|a_k - a_{k-1}|≤1$, we get $j-i≥2$. Construct a new sequence $B: a_i-t, a_{i+1}-t, ..., a_j-t$, this sequence has at least 3 terms;
4. The new sequence satisfies $(a_i-t)(a_j-t)=(m-t)(M-t)<0$, and $|(a_{k+1}-t)-(a_k-t)|=|a_{k+1}-a_k|≤1$;
5. From the conclusion of (Ⅱ), there exists $a_r-t=0$ ($r \in \{i+1,...,j-1\}$) in the new sequence, that is $a_r=t$;
6. So $S(A_N)=Nt=Na_r$. If $i>j$, construct the sequence $t-a_j,t-a_{j+1},...,t-a_i$, similarly we can prove that there exists $a_r=t$;
7. In summary, there exists $a_r$ in the sequence $A_N$ such that $S(A_N)=N \cdot a_r$.
